 =        \n| relatives = \n| callsign = \n| awards = \n| website = \n| allegiance =\n| motive = \n| conviction = Murder (2 counts) (May 7, 2018)<br />Murder (2 counts) (March 1, 2019)<br />Murder (1 count) (September 11, 2019)\n| reward_amount = \n| capture_status = \n| wanted_by = \n| partners = \n| wanted_since = \n| time_at_large = \n| escaped = \n| escape_end = \n| comments = \n| victims = 5 known (one known as \"Jane Doe\" who was kidnapped and raped multiple times was able to escape); Multiple bodies found, believed to be victims of Grate.\n| date = \n| time = \n| beginyear = 2006\n| endyear = 2016\n| country = United States\n| states = [[Ohio]]\n| locations = [[Ashland County, Ohio|Ashland County]], [[Marion County, Ohio|Marion County]], [[Richland County, Ohio|Richland County]]\n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| injuries = \n| weapons = \n| apprehended = September 13, 2016\n| imprisoned = \n| module =\n| signature =\n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Shawn Michael Grate''' (born August 8, 1976<ref name=WMFD_69898>{{cite news|last1=Jackman|first1=Jay|title=23 Felony Count Indictments Against Convicted Serial Killer|url=http://www.northcentralohio.com/news/single.asp?story=69898|accessdate=September 23, 2016|work=WMFD|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026233125/http://www.northcentralohio.com/news/single.asp?story=69898|archive-date=October 26, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>) is an [[Demography of the United States|American]] convicted [[serial killer]] who was convicted on two counts of [[Aggravation (law)|aggravated]] [[murder]] on May 7, 2018, in [[Ashland County, Ohio|Ashland County]], [[Ohio]], pleaded guilty to two additional murders on March 1, 2019 in [[Richland County, Ohio]], and who pleaded guilty to an additional murder on September 11, 2019 in [[Marion County, Ohio]].\n\n==Biography==\nGrate graduated from [[River Valley High School (Caledonia, Ohio)|River Valley High School]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.richlandsource.com/news/grate-s-ex-wife-releases-statement/article_7ebfacc8-7b57-11e6-ab9d-63cfe72c082d.html\n |title=Grate's ex-wife releases statement\n |last=Carr\n |first=Dillon\n |date=September 15, 2016\n |website=Richland Source\n |publisher=\n |access-date=November 30, 2017\n |quote= }}</ref>\n\nA [[grand jury]] [[indict]]ed Grate on two counts of [[Aggravation (law)|aggravated]] [[murder]] in the deaths of two women, Stacey Stanley and Elizabeth Griffith, and the [[kidnapping]] and multiple [[Rape|sexual assaults]] of an unidentified woman whose [[9-1-1|911]] call to [[Ashland, Ohio|Ashland]] police led to Grate's arrest on September 13, 2016.  In court documents her name has been [[Redaction|redacted]]. She is being referred to as \"Jane Doe\". Grate was indicted on 23 counts, all first, second, or third-degree [[Felony|felonies]]; lesser charges include [[breaking and entering]], [[burglary]], and [[tampering with evidence]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tunnell|first1=Christopher|title=PDF Released: Grate Indictment 22 Sept 16|url=https://twitter.com/AshlandCoPros/status/779036910719229952|website=Twitter|accessdate=September 23, 2016}}</ref>  \n\nHe was represented in court by [[Public defender|court-appointed attorney]] Rolf Whitney,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sams|first1=Dylan|title=Grate pleads not guilty to two counts of murder, one count kidnapping|url=http://www.times-gazette.com/local%20news/2016/09/19/grate-pleads-not-guilty-to-two-counts-of-murder-one-count-kidnapping|accessdate=September 26, 2016|work=Ashland Times-Gazette}}</ref> who entered a plea of not guilty on all charges on behalf of Grate.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dunning|first1=Shanice|title=Suspected serial killer Shawn Grate pleads not guilty|url=http://www.cleveland19.com/story/33276947/suspected-serial-killer-shawn-grate-to-be-arraigned-thurs|accessdate=October 10, 2016|work=Cleveland 19 News}}</ref> In a press interview Grate confessed to five murders.<ref name=QAndACleveland19>{{cite news|last1=Nist|first1=Cassie|title=Q&A from jail: Shawn Grate says his victims didn't want to live|url=http://www.cleveland19.com/story/33343964/suspected-serial-killer-shawn-grate-grants-interview-from-ashland-county-jail|accessdate=October 10, 2016|work=Cleveland 19 News}}</ref> Grate's attorneys later filed a plea of not guilty by reason of insanity.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Steer|first1=Jen|title=Accused Ashland serial killer pleads insanity|url=http://fox8.com/2016/12/28/accused-ashland-serial-killer-pleads-insanity/|accessdate=January 4, 2017|work=WJW Fox 8 Cleveland|date=December 28, 2016}}</ref> His trial date was set for November 6, 2017,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mills|first1=Emily|title=Shawn Grate's trial date set for next November|url=http://www.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/2016/10/31/shawn-grates-trial-date-set-next-november/93086374/|accessdate=November 7, 2016|work=Mansfield News Journal|date=October 31, 2016}}</ref> and was later delayed to April 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Busbey|first1=Tim|title=Accused Ashland serial killer Shawn Grate's trial delayed until April 9|url=http://www.richlandsource.com/ashland_source/accused-ashland-serial-killer-shawn-grate-s-trial-delayed-until/article_3dda90c4-8c31-11e7-81ea-7b54d0d5f78e.html|accessdate=August 29, 2017|work=Richland Source|date=August 28, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sams|first1=Dylan|title=Trial for Shawn Grate rescheduled for April 2018|url=https://www.times-gazette.com/local%20news/2017/08/28/trial-for-shawn-grate-rescheduled-for-april-2018|accessdate=August 29, 2017|work=Ashland Times-Gazette|date=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Trial of accused serial killer Shawn Grate delayed until next year|url=http://www.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/2017/08/28/trial-accused-serial-killer-grate-delayed/607622001/|accessdate=August 29, 2017|work=Mansfield News Journal|date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAshland County [[prosecutor]] Christopher R. Tunnell said that given the \"...depraved actions and the gruesome evidence\", he would seek the [[death penalty]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ashland prosecutor seeks death penalty against suspected serial killer|url=http://nbc4i.com/2016/09/22/ashland-prosecutor-seeks-death-penalty-against-suspected-serial-killer/|accessdate=September 26, 2016|work=WCMH-TV NBC4}}</ref>\n\nShawn Grate has also been charged in the deaths of his former girlfriend Candice Cunningham and Rebekah Leicy in neighboring Richland County,<ref>{{cite news|title=Convicted murderer Shawn Grate pleads not guilty to Richland County charges|url=https://eu.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/2018/09/13/convicted-murderer-shawn-grate-pleads-not-guilty-richland-charges/1291554002/|accessdate=September 14, 2018|work=Mansfield News Journal|date=September 13, 2018}}</ref> and has also been charged in the death of Dana Nicole Lowrey, 23, who died in 2006 and was found in 2007 in Marion County.<ref name=NBC4_9_20_16>{{cite news|title=Ashland killer connection reopens 2015 case|url=http://nbc4i.com/2016/09/20/ashland-killer-connection-reopens-2015-case/|accessdate=September 26, 2016|work=WCMH-TV NBC4}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Serial killer Shawn Grate charged in Marion County in woman's 2006 death  |url=https://eu.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/crime/2019/06/06/serial-killer-shawn-grate-charged-marion-county-womans-2007-death/1365551001/|accessdate=June 6, 2019|work=Mansfield News Journal|date=June 6, 2019}}</ref>  In the second of two letters he sent to [[Cleveland]] news station [[WEWS-TV|WEWS]] (News 5 Cleveland) reporter Megan Hickey, Grate attributed his motives to \"[[Welfare|government assistance]]\", writing that it took his victims' minds.  \"They were already dead, just their bodies were flopping wherever it can flop but their minds were already dead! The state took their minds. Once they started receiving their monthly checks\".  Grate claimed he once received a $197 [[Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program|food card]] and that he \"never was able to receive any encouragement, though many bodies received 700\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hickey|first1=Megan|title=Suspected serial killer Shawn Grate reveals \"why\" he murdered victims in letters to News 5|url=http://www.newsnet5.com/news/local-news/suspected-serial-killer-shawn-grate-reveals-why-he-murdered-victims-in-letters-to-news-5|accessdate=October 6, 2016|work=WEWS News 5 Cleveland}}</ref>\n\nAfter Grate gave details of the murders to two different news organizations while in custody, attorneys for the defense and prosecution jointly requested and obtained a [[gag order]] preventing Grate from communicating any further with the media.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barbash|first1=Fred|title=The twisted confessions of Shawn Grate, who says he killed 5 women|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/10/14/the-twisted-confessions-of-shawn-grate-who-says-he-killed-5-women/|accessdate=October 24, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> On January 6, 2017, a competency hearing determined Grate is fit to stand trial.<ref>{{cite news|title=Grate competent to stand trial|url=http://www.times-gazette.com/local%20news/2017/01/06/grate-competent-to-stand-trial|accessdate=January 10, 2017|work=Ashland Times-Gazette|date=January 6, 2017}}</ref> An evaluation released March 6, based on a January 17 assessment to evaluate Grate's claim of insanity, declared that he was not insane at the time the crimes were committed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Caudill|first1=Mark|title=Grate ruled competent to stand trial|url=http://www.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/local/2017/01/06/grate-ruled-competent-stand-trial/96238260/|accessdate=January 10, 2017|work=Mansfield News Journal|date=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Caudil|first1=Mark|title=Evaluation: Shawn Grate not insane at time of killings|url=http://www.wkyc.com/news/local/ohio/evaluation-shawn-grate-not-insane-at-time-of-killings/420130608|accessdate=March 20, 2017|work=WKYC|date=March 6, 2017}}</ref> Grate's counsel then withdrew the plea of not guilty by reason of insanity on April 7, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Busbey|first1=Tim|title=Shawn Grate's attorneys withdraw insanity plea|url=http://www.richlandsource.com/ashland_source/shawn-grate-s-attorneys-withdraw-insanity-plea/article_a3fd8f4c-1bab-11e7-96da-53a4563772d1.html|accessdate=April 19, 2017|work=Richland Source|date=April 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>https://www.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/2020/02/04/mansfield-house-where-serial-killer-shawn-grate-stayed-demolished/4654001002/</ref>\n\n[[File:House at 363 Covert Court, Ashland, OH.jpg|thumb|363 Covert Court in Ashland, OH where Grate was arrested, a public memorial is in front of the house. The house has since been demolished.]]\nIn a settlement with the owner, the City of Ashland obtained ownership of the house where Grate was apprehended, two bodies were discovered, and a kidnapped woman was rescued by police. The city is pursuing a federal grant with the intention of demolishing the house.<ref name=\"Ashland Times-Gazette\">{{cite news|last1=Sams|first1=Dylan|title=Pump House to sign properties over to city in foreclosure case|url=http://www.times-gazette.com/news/20170912/pump-house-to-sign-properties-over-to-city-in-foreclosure-case|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=Ashland Times-Gazette|date=September 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sams|first1=Dylan|title=Ashland wants to demolish the houses where Shawn Grate was found last year|url=https://www.times-gazette.com/local%20news/2017/07/14/ashland-wants-to-demolish-the-houses-where-shawn-grate-was-found-last-year|accessdate=July 17, 2017|agency=Ashland Times-Gazette|date=July 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\u201cThere is a settlement agreement among the parties that essentially obligates the Pump House to transfer all property that is the subject of this action to the city of Ashland and transfer their title thereto, provided that the city pays off the sums owed to the county for delinquent taxes and to the Muskingum Watershed District,\u201d said Andrew Bush, assistant law director for the city of Ashland.<ref name=\"Ashland Times-Gazette\"/>\n\n== Trials ==\nGrate's trial for the Ashland crimes began with two weeks of jury selection on April 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNaull|first1=Courtney|title=Jury selection begins in Shawn Grate case|url=http://www.richlandsource.com/ashland_source/jury-selection-begins-in-shawn-grate-case/article_4a052884-3bed-11e8-9772-f7342d9a5bf9.html|accessdate=April 9, 2018|work=Richland Source|date=April 9, 2018|language=en}}</ref> The trial began with opening statements on April 23.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sams|first1=Dylan|title=Prosecutor: Shawn Grate case \u201cnot a whodunnit\u201d|url=http://www.times-gazette.com/news/20180423/shawn-grate-not-whodunnit-case-prosecutor-says|accessdate=April 23, 2018|work=Ashland Times-Gazette|date=April 23, 2018|language=en}}</ref> On May 2, Grate pleaded guilty to 15 of the charges against him.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sams|first1=Dylan|title=Accused killer Grate pleads guilty to 15 non-murder charges|url=http://www.times-gazette.com/news/20180502/accused-killer-grate-pleads-guilty-to-15-non-murder-charges|accessdate=May 3, 2018|agency=Ashland Times-Gazette|date=May 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Accused Ashland serial killer Shawn Grate pleads guilty to several charges|url=http://fox8.com/2018/05/02/accused-ashland-serial-killer-shawn-grate-pleading-guilty-to-several-charges/|accessdate=May 3, 2018|work=WJW Fox 8 Cleveland|date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> On May 7, Grate was found guilty of murdering Stacey Stanley and Elizabeth Griffith.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jury finds Shawn Grate guilty of murder, sexual assault in Ohio|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/ohio-serial-killer-case-sent-jury-death-two-women-n872001|accessdate=May 8, 2018|work=NBC NEWS|date=May 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Accused serial killer Shawn Grate found guilty of aggravated murder, kidnapping|url=http://fox8.com/2018/05/07/closing-arguments-set-for-today-in-trial-of-accused-serial-killer/|accessdate=May 8, 2018|work=WJW Fox 8 Cleveland|date=May 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sams|first1=Dylan|title=GRATE TRIAL: Guilty on all 8 counts|url=http://www.times-gazette.com/news/20180507/grate-trial-guilty-on-all-8-counts|accessdate=May 8, 2018|work=Ashland Times-Gazette|date=May 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> On June 1, Grate was sentenced to death.<ref name=\"News Journal Death Sentence\">{{cite news|title=Crowd in court applauds death sentence for Shawn Grate|url=https://eu.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/2018/06/01/shawn-grate-sentenced-death-2016-murders/645107002/|accessdate=June 1, 2018|work=Mansfield News Journal|date=June 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sams |first1=Dylan |title=Judge sentences Grate to death, families mourn |url=http://www.times-gazette.com/news/20180601/judge-sentences-grate-to-death-in-two-murders |accessdate=June 1, 2018 |work=Ashland Times-Gazette |date=June 1, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> An initial execution date was set upon conviction for [[List of offenders executed in the United States in 2018|September 13, 2018]],<ref name=\"News Journal Death Sentence\"/> however the execution was stayed due to a pending appeal to the Ohio Supreme Court.<ref name=SourceSept18>{{cite news |last1=McNaull |first1=Courtney |title=Serial killer Shawn Grate case resumes on Sept. 25 |url=https://www.richlandsource.com/news/serial-killer-shawn-grate-case-resumes-on-sept/article_4b37d216-bab8-11e8-a225-977fabd6e654.html |accessdate=November 2, 2018 |work=Richland Source |issue=September 24, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDefense counsel in the trial were Robert Whitney and Rolf Whitney. The prosecution team was Ashland Prosecutor Chris Tunnell, Medina County Assistant Prosecutor Michael McNamara and Special Prosecutor Mark Weaver.<ref name=\"News Journal Death Sentence\"/>\n\nOn March 1, 2019, Grate pleaded guilty in the murders of Rebekah Leicy and Candice Cunningham and was sentenced to life in prison without parole for the murder of Leicy and 17 years to life for the other charges with the sentences running consecutively.<ref>{{cite news|title=Serial killer Grate pleads guilty to killing 2 women in Richland County |url=https://eu.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/2019/03/01/serial-killer-grate-pleads-guilty-2-murders/3019380002/|accessdate=March 1, 2019|work=Mansfield News Journal|date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 11, 2019, Grate pleaded guilty in the murder of Dana Lowrey and was sentenced to life in prison without parole plus 16 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Convicted killer Shawn Grate sentenced to another life term in Marion County death |url=https://www.10tv.com/article/convicted-killer-shawn-grate-sentenced-another-life-term-marion-county-death-2019-sep|accessdate=September 12, 2019|work=10TV|date=September 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Death-row's Grate gets prison term for Marion murder, his first |url=https://eu.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/crime/2019/09/11/serial-killer-shawn-grate-death-row-gets-prison-term-marion-first-murder/2285750001/|accessdate=September 12, 2019|work=Mansfield News Journal|date=September 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Convicted serial killer Shawn Grate pleads guilty to Marion County murder |url=https://www.cleveland19.com/2019/09/11/convicted-serial-killer-shawn-grate-pleads-guilty-marion-county-murder/|accessdate=September 12, 2019|work=Cleveland19|date=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Victims ==\n\n===Kidnapping Victim===\nWhile Grate slept, the victim identified by the indictment only as \"Jane Doe\"<ref name=WMFD_69898 /> called 911 from the Ashland house where Grate had held her for three days. She was safely rescued by Ashland police. Because she was the victim of a sexual assault, police declined to reveal her identity.<ref>{{cite web|title=What we know: Shawn Grate tied to 5 deaths, 1 abduction|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/crime/2016/09/20/shawn-grate-what-we-know/90731792/|website=Cincinnati.com|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref> Grate claims he did not plan to kill her and that they were going to get married.<ref name=QAndACleveland19 />\n\n===Stacey Stanley A.K.A. Stacey Hicks===\nStanley's family had reported her missing the week before Grate was arrested. Her body was found at the Ashland house where Grate was arrested.<ref name=time_9-20-16>{{cite news|last1=Samuelson|first1=Kate|title=Man Linked to at Least 5 Women's Deaths Is 'Obviously a Serial Killer,' Sheriff Says|url=http://time.com/4501103/shawn-grate-murder-kidnapping-obviously-serial-killer/|accessdate=September 20, 2016|work=TIME}}</ref> She is also known as Stacy Hicks. An autopsy concluded she was strangled to death.<ref name=WEWSjan17>{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Bob|title=Autopsy report reveals two of Shawn Grate's alleged victims were strangled to death|url=http://www.newsnet5.com/news/local-news/oh-ashland/autopsy-report-reveals-two-of-shawn-grates-alleged-victims-were-strangled-to-death|accessdate=January 4, 2017|work=WEWS|date=January 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Elizabeth Griffith===\nGriffith had been missing for about a month before Grate was arrested. Her body was found at the Ashland house where Grate was arrested.<ref name=time_9-20-16 /> An autopsy concluded she was strangled to death.<ref name=WEWSjan17 />\n\n===Candice Cunningham===\nGrate led police to what he claimed was Cunningham's body in neighboring [[Richland County, Ohio|Richland County]] on the day of his arrest.<ref>{{cite news|last1=L'Heureux|first1=Catie|title=A Serial Killer's Victim Made a 911 Call That Helped Police Link the Cases of 5 Murdered Women|url=http://nymag.com/thecut/2016/09/5-women-linked-to-serial-killer-shawn-grate-in-ohio.html|accessdate=September 20, 2016|work=New York Magazine}}</ref> Police found the body behind a house that had previously burned down. The Richland County Sheriff's office officially confirmed that the body found was Cunningham's on November 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carr|first1=Dillon|title=Candice Cunningham identified as 3rd victim in Grate case|url=http://www.richlandsource.com/news/candice-cunningham-identified-as-rd-victim-in-grate-case/article_608d8396-a042-11e6-86bd-0ff8b86074df.html|accessdate=November 7, 2016|work=Richland Source|date=November 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Rebekah Leicy===\nBased on information supplied by Grate, police have reopened the investigation into Leicy's death. Her body was found in March 2015, and her death was originally ruled a drug overdose.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Whitmire|first1=Lou|title=Grate provides Mansfield police with tips in Leicy case|url=http://www.mansfieldnewsjournal.com/story/news/2016/09/19/mansfield-police-searching-evidence-leicy-investigation/90715336/|accessdate=September 20, 2016|work=Mansfield News Journal}}</ref> Grate says he strangled her after she stole $4 from him in a bar.<ref name=QAndACleveland19 />\n\n===Dana Lowrey===\nGrate claims to have killed another woman who was found dead in [[Marion County, Ohio|Marion County]], Ohio in 2007 who remained unidentified for 12 years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barbash|first1=Fred|title='He's obviously a serial killer': Deaths of at least 5 women now linked, probed by Ohio police|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/09/20/hes-obviously-a-serial-killer-deaths-of-at-least-5-women-now-linked-probed-by-ohio-police/|accessdate=September 20, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> He has stated he believes her name was Dana.<ref name=QAndACleveland19 /> In January 2018, isotope analysis indicated she was likely from the southern United States.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Volpenhein|first1=Sarah|title=New tests could help identify alleged Shawn Grate victim in Marion County|url=https://www.marionstar.com/story/news/crime/2018/04/11/new-leads-naming-first-grate-victim/507374002/|accessdate=April 12, 2018|work=Marion Star|date=April 11, 2018|language=en}}</ref> The victim was identified in June 2019 by the [[DNA Doe Project]] as Dana Nicole Lowrey, 23, of [[Minden, Louisiana]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Marion County Sheriff identifying remains believed to be Shawn Grate's first victim |url=https://myfox28columbus.com/news/local/sheriff-sharing-new-details-on-remains-believed-to-be-shawn-grates-first-victim |accessdate=June 4, 2019 |work=WTTE |date=June 4, 2019}}</ref> Lowrey had two daughters aged one and five  at the time of her death and was separated from her daughters\u2019 father.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/officials-identify-remains-woman-believed-be-shawn-grates-first-victim-2019-jun|title=Officials identify remains of woman believed to be Shawn Grate's first victim|last=Bailey|first=Brittany|date=June 4, 2019|website=WBNS-10TV Columbus, Ohio News, Weather & Sports|language=en|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grate, Shawn}}\n\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American kidnappers]]\n[[Category:American rapists]]\n[[Category:American criminals]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Ohio]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to death by Ohio]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ars3nic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrials", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shawn_Grate"}
{"title_page": "Frank Bonham", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=June 2010}}\n'''Frank Bonham''' (February 25, [[1914 in literature|1914]] &ndash; [[1988 in literature|1988]]) was an author of [[Western (genre)|Westerns]] and [[young adult literature|young adult novels]]. Bonham wrote 48 novels, as well as TV scripts. He is proven to be the most boring person in American history.\n\nBonham was born in [[Los Angeles]].  He was a [[University of California at Los Angeles|UCLA]] graduate.<ref>''Durango Street'', Penguin, 1999, {{ISBN|0-14-130309-3}} author biography</ref>\n\nBonham was known for his works for [[young adult fiction|young adult]]s written in the 1960s, with tough, realistic urban settings,<ref>[http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Author/AuthorPage/0,,1000004213,00.html]</ref> including ''[[The Nitty Gritty (novel)|The Nitty Gritty]]'' and ''[[Durango Street]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://stage30.scholastic.com/tbw/viewWorkDetail.do?workId=1153309& |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-06-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104025712/http://stage30.scholastic.com/tbw/viewWorkDetail.do?workId=1153309& |archive-date=2013-11-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as for his westerns. Several of his works have been published posthumously, many of which were drawn from his [[pulp magazine]] stories, originally published between 1941 and 1952. ''Durango Street'' was an [[ALA Notable Book]].\n\n== Novels ==\n*''Lost Stage Valley'' (1948)\n*''Snaketrack'' (1951)\n*''Blood on the Land'' (1952)\n*''Night Raid'' (1954)\n*''The Feud at Spanish Ford'' (1954)\n*''Rawhide Guns'' (1955)\n*''Border Guns'' (1956)\n*''Defiance Mountain'' (1956)\n*''Hardrock'' (1958)\n*''Tough Country'' (1958)\n*''Last Stage West'' (1959)\n*''The Outcast of Crooked River'' (1959)\n*''Sound of Gunfire'' (1959)\n*''Burma Rifles: A story of Merrill's Marauders'' (1960)\n*''One for Sleep'' (1960)\n*''The Skin Game'' (1961)\n*''The Wild Breed'' (1962)\n*''War Beneath the Sea'' (1962)\n*''Trago'' (1962)\n*''By Her Own Hand'' (1963)\n*''Deepwater Challenge'' (1963)\n*''Honor Bound' (1963)\n*''The Loud, Resounding Sea'' (1963)\n*''Cast a Long Shadow'' (1964)\n*''Logan's Choice'' (1964)\n*''Speedway Contender'' (1964)\n*''Durango Street'' (1965)  {{ISBN|0-525-28950-X}}\n*''Mystery in Little Tokyo'' (1966)\n*''Mystery of the Red Tide'' (1966)\n*''The Ghost Front'' (1968)\n*''Mystery of the Fat Cat'' (1968)\n*''Nitty Gritty'' (1968)\n*''The Vagabundos'' (1969)\n*''Viva Chicano'' (1970)<ref>[http://eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/search/detailmini.jsp?_nfpb=true&_&ERICExtSearch_SearchValue_0=ED046562&ERICExtSearch_SearchType_0=no&accno=ED046562]</ref>\n*''Chief'' (1971)\n*''Cool Cat'' (1972)\n*''The Friends of the Loony Lake Monster'' (1972)\n*''A Dream of Ghosts'' (1973)\n*''Golden Bees of Tulami'' (1974)\n*''The Missing Persons League'' (1976)\n*''Hey, Big Spender'' (1976)\n*''Bold Passage'' (1977)\n*''Rascals from Haskell's Gym'' (1977)\n*''Devilhorn'' (1978)\n*''The Forever Formula'' (1979)\n*''Break for the Border'' (1980)\n*''Fort Hogan'' (1980)\n*''Gimme an H, Gimme an E, Gimme an L, Gimme A P'' (1980)\n*''Premonitions'' (1984)\n*''The Eye of the Hunter'' (1989)\n*''Burn Him Out'' (1998)\n*''Furnace Flat'' (2000)\n*''Stage Trails West: Western Stories'' (2002)\n*''The Last Mustang: Western Stories'' (2003)\n*''Outcasts of Rebel Creek: A Western Quartet'' (2004)\n*''Dakota Man: Western Stories'' (2007)\n*''Devil's Graze: Western Stories'' (2008)\n*''The Dark Border: A Western Quartet'' (2009)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/b/frank-bonham/ Bibliography at Fantastic Fiction]\n{{Portal|Children and Young Adult Literature}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonham, Frank}}\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:American writers of young adult literature]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n\n\n{{US-child-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=June 2010}}\n'''Frank Bonham''' (February 25, [[1914 in literature|1914]] &ndash; [[1988 in literature|1988]]) was an author of [[Western (genre)|Westerns]] and [[young adult literature|young adult novels]]. Bonham wrote 48 novels, as well as TV scripts.\n\nBonham was born in [[Los Angeles]].  He was a [[University of California at Los Angeles|UCLA]] graduate.<ref>''Durango Street'', Penguin, 1999, {{ISBN|0-14-130309-3}} author biography</ref>\n\nBonham was known for his works for [[young adult fiction|young adult]]s written in the 1960s, with tough, realistic urban settings,<ref>[http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Author/AuthorPage/0,,1000004213,00.html]</ref> including ''[[The Nitty Gritty (novel)|The Nitty Gritty]]'' and ''[[Durango Street]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://stage30.scholastic.com/tbw/viewWorkDetail.do?workId=1153309& |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-06-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104025712/http://stage30.scholastic.com/tbw/viewWorkDetail.do?workId=1153309& |archive-date=2013-11-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as for his westerns. Several of his works have been published posthumously, many of which were drawn from his [[pulp magazine]] stories, originally published between 1941 and 1952. ''Durango Street'' was an [[ALA Notable Book]].\n\n== Novels ==\n*''Lost Stage Valley'' (1948)\n*''Snaketrack'' (1951)\n*''Blood on the Land'' (1952)\n*''Night Raid'' (1954)\n*''The Feud at Spanish Ford'' (1954)\n*''Rawhide Guns'' (1955)\n*''Border Guns'' (1956)\n*''Defiance Mountain'' (1956)\n*''Hardrock'' (1958)\n*''Tough Country'' (1958)\n*''Last Stage West'' (1959)\n*''The Outcast of Crooked River'' (1959)\n*''Sound of Gunfire'' (1959)\n*''Burma Rifles: A story of Merrill's Marauders'' (1960)\n*''One for Sleep'' (1960)\n*''The Skin Game'' (1961)\n*''The Wild Breed'' (1962)\n*''War Beneath the Sea'' (1962)\n*''Trago'' (1962)\n*''By Her Own Hand'' (1963)\n*''Deepwater Challenge'' (1963)\n*''Honor Bound' (1963)\n*''The Loud, Resounding Sea'' (1963)\n*''Cast a Long Shadow'' (1964)\n*''Logan's Choice'' (1964)\n*''Speedway Contender'' (1964)\n*''Durango Street'' (1965)  {{ISBN|0-525-28950-X}}\n*''Mystery in Little Tokyo'' (1966)\n*''Mystery of the Red Tide'' (1966)\n*''The Ghost Front'' (1968)\n*''Mystery of the Fat Cat'' (1968)\n*''Nitty Gritty'' (1968)\n*''The Vagabundos'' (1969)\n*''Viva Chicano'' (1970)<ref>[http://eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/search/detailmini.jsp?_nfpb=true&_&ERICExtSearch_SearchValue_0=ED046562&ERICExtSearch_SearchType_0=no&accno=ED046562]</ref>\n*''Chief'' (1971)\n*''Cool Cat'' (1972)\n*''The Friends of the Loony Lake Monster'' (1972)\n*''A Dream of Ghosts'' (1973)\n*''Golden Bees of Tulami'' (1974)\n*''The Missing Persons League'' (1976)\n*''Hey, Big Spender'' (1976)\n*''Bold Passage'' (1977)\n*''Rascals from Haskell's Gym'' (1977)\n*''Devilhorn'' (1978)\n*''The Forever Formula'' (1979)\n*''Break for the Border'' (1980)\n*''Fort Hogan'' (1980)\n*''Gimme an H, Gimme an E, Gimme an L, Gimme A P'' (1980)\n*''Premonitions'' (1984)\n*''The Eye of the Hunter'' (1989)\n*''Burn Him Out'' (1998)\n*''Furnace Flat'' (2000)\n*''Stage Trails West: Western Stories'' (2002)\n*''The Last Mustang: Western Stories'' (2003)\n*''Outcasts of Rebel Creek: A Western Quartet'' (2004)\n*''Dakota Man: Western Stories'' (2007)\n*''Devil's Graze: Western Stories'' (2008)\n*''The Dark Border: A Western Quartet'' (2009)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/b/frank-bonham/ Bibliography at Fantastic Fiction]\n{{Portal|Children and Young Adult Literature}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonham, Frank}}\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:American writers of young adult literature]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n\n\n{{US-child-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "65.29.116.198", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added a true fact)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Bonham"}
{"title_page": "Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)", "text_new": "{{redirect|Day-O|the television film|Day-O (film)}}\n{{For|the song that samples the lyric \"6 foot, 7 foot, 8 foot bunch\"|6 Foot 7 Foot}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name        = Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)\n| cover       = \n| alt         =\n| type        = single\n| artist      = [[Harry Belafonte]]\n| album       = [[Calypso (album)|Calypso]]\n| B-side      = \"Star-O\"\n| released    = 1956\n| format      = [[Vinyl record]] (7-inch, 10-inch)\n| recorded    = 1955\n| studio      = Grand Ballroom, [[Webster Hall]], [[New York City]]\n| venue       = \n| genre       = [[Mento]]\n| length      = 3:02\n| label       = [[RCA Victor]]\n| writer      = \n| producer    =\n| prev_title  = [[Mary's Boy Child]]\n| prev_year   = 1954\n| next_title  = Hold 'Em Joe\n| next_year   = 1957\n}}\n[[File:Harry Belafonte Almanac 1954 b.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Harry Belafonte, Almanac, 1954 Feb. 18.]]\n\n'''\"Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)\"''' is a traditional [[Music of Jamaica|Jamaican folk song]]. The song has [[mento]] influences, but it is commonly classified as an example of the better known [[calypso music]].\n\nIt is a [[work song]], from the point of view of dock workers working the night shift loading [[banana]]s onto ships. The lyrics describe how daylight has come, their shift is over, and they want their work to be counted up so that they can go home.\n\nThe best-known version was released by American singer [[Harry Belafonte]] in 1956 and later became one of his signature songs. That same year [[The Tarriers]] released an alternative version that incorporated the chorus of another Jamaican [[folk song]], \"Hill and Gully Rider\". The Tarriers version was recorded by [[Shirley Bassey]] in 1957<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Shirley-Bassey-The-Banana-Boat-Song/master/1461636</ref> for her 1959 album ''[[The Bewitching Miss Bassey]]''.<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Shirley-Bassey-The-Bewitching-Miss-Bassey/master/648488</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nThe song originated as a Jamaican folk song. It was thought to be sung by Jamaican banana workers, with a repeated melody and refrain ([[Call and response (music)|call and response]]); to each set lyric, the workers made a response. There were numerous versions of lyrics, some likely improvised on the spot by the singers. The song was probably created around the second half of the nineteenth century or the first half of the twentieth century, where there was [[History of Jamaica#Decline of the sugar industry|a rise of the banana trade in Jamaica]].\n\nThe song was first recorded by [[Trinidad]]ian singer [[Edric Connor]] and his band \"Edric Connor and the Caribbeans\" on the 1952 album ''Songs From Jamaica''; the song was called \"Day Dah Light\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mentomusic.com/edricConner.htm |title=Edric Connor, Louise Bennett and Jamaican Folk Music |publisher=Mento Music |date= |accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref> Belafonte based his version on Connor's 1952 and [[Louise Bennett]]'s 1954 recordings.<ref>The Louise Bennett version of ''Day O (The Banana Boat Song)'' is available and documented in both French and English on the ''Jamaica &ndash; Mento 1951&ndash;1958'' album (2009)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fremeaux.com/index.php?option=com_virtuemart&page=shop.livrets&content_id=5362&product_id=1176&category_id=128 |title=Fr\u00e9meaux & Associ\u00e9s \u00e9diteur, La Librairie Sonore |website=Fremeaux.com |date=1932-06-19 |accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1955, American singer-songwriters [[Lord Burgess]] and [[William Attaway]] wrote a version of the lyrics for ''[[the Colgate Comedy Hour]]'', in which the song was performed by [[Harry Belafonte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dGSnsW6rA6EC&pg=PA186|title=Trinidad Carnival: The Cultural Politics of a Transnational Festival|first1=Garth L.|last1=Green|first2=Philip W.|last2=Scher|date=28 March 2007|page=186|publisher=[[Indiana University Press]]|accessdate=1 September 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref> Belafonte recorded the song for [[RCA Victor]]  and this is the version that is best known to listeners today, as it reached number five on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' charts in 1957 and later became Belafonte's [[signature song]]. Side two of Belafonte's 1956 ''Calypso'' album opens with \"Star O\", a song referring to the day shift ending when the first star is seen in the sky. During recording, when asked for its title, Harry spells, \"Day Done Light\".\n\nAlso in 1956, folk singer [[Bob Gibson (musician)|Bob Gibson]], who had traveled to Jamaica and heard the song, taught his version to the folk band [[The Tarriers]]. They recorded a version of that song that incorporated the chorus of \"Hill and Gully Rider\", another Jamaican folk song. This release became their biggest hit, reaching number four on the pop charts, where it outperformed Belafonte's version. The Tarriers' version was recorded by [[Shirley Bassey]] in 1957 and it became a hit in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/The%20Banana%20Boat%20Song |title=ChartArchive - Shirley Bassey - The Banana Boat Song |website=Archive.is |date= |accessdate=2016-08-22 |df= }}</ref> The Tarriers, or some subset of the three members of the group ([[Erik Darling]], [[Bob Carey (musician)|Bob Carey]] and [[Alan Arkin]], later better known as an actor) are sometimes credited as the writers of the song; their version combined elements of another song and was thus newly created.\n\n== Covers ==\n* [[Sarah Vaughan]] recorded the song for [[Mercury Records]] in 1956.\n* [[The Fontane Sisters]] mimicked The Tarriers version in a recording of the song for [[Dot Records]] in 1956.  It charted to number 13 in the US in 1957.\n* [[Barry Frank]] released a version for Bell in 1957.<ref name=bell>{{cite web | title = Barry Frank recorded or participated in at least the following 54 song(s) | url = http://www.bellrecords.nl/?wp=performers| publisher = Bell Records | accessdate = 8 October 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Jimmie Rodgers (pop singer)|Jimmie Rodgers]] recorded the song for [[Dot Records]] which was released in September, 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Jimmie-Rodgers-The-Banana-Boat-Song/release/4702109 |title=Jimmie Rodgers (2) - The Banana Boat Song (Vinyl) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref>\n* [[The Techniques]] covered the song in 1967.\n* [[The Kinks]] did a semi-serious version on the 1972 album ''[[Everybody's in Show-Biz]]''\n* Children's singer [[Raffi (musician)|Raffi]] recorded this song for his 1980 album, ''[[Baby Beluga]]'', releasing it as a single. \n* Italian singer [[Mina (Italian singer)|Mina]] covered the song under the title \"Banana Boat\" on the 1984 album [[Catene (album)|Catene]].\n* [[Chuck Brown|Chuck Brown & the Soul Searchers]] performed a [[go-go]] rendition for the album ''[[Go Go Swing Live]]'' (1986).\n* [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]] released a Funk version of the song on his 1989 album ''[[The Cinderella Theory]]''.\n* [[Hasil Adkins]] recorded a [[rockabilly]] version of this song that was included on the 1990 [[Norton Records]] album, ''[[Peanut Butter Rock and Roll]]''.\n* Jamaican singer [[Shaggy (musician)|Shaggy]] recorded a dancehall version for his 1995 album ''[[Boombastic (album)|Boombastic]]''.\n* The Kidsongs Kids sing this song on \"I'd Like to Teach the World to Sing\". There is also an instrumental [[Outro (music)|outro]] as heard on CDs and cassettes.\n* German dance band [[Scooter (band)|Scooter]] made a cover version of the song in 2003. Originally, it was intended to release as a Ratty track but the plan cancelled and the song released under the name \"Beetle Juice pres. Rick Maniac & Dr. Loop\".\n* The Polish sea-shanty band [[Banana Boat]] sings this song on their 2004 album \"A morze tak, a mo\u017ce nie\".\n* British [[New wave music|new wave]] band [[The Police (band)|The Police]] were known to include snippets of the song during early live performances of their own track '[[Reggatta de Blanc (instrumental)|Reggatta de Blanc]]'.\n* Australian children's entertainers [[The Wiggles]] cover it in their 2008 album ''[[You Make Me Feel Like Dancing (album)|You Make Me Feel Like Dancing]]''.\n* [[Vocal Sampling]] have performed an [[a cappella]] version, which is included in their 2008 album ''Akapelleando''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Vocal-Sampling-Akapelleando/release/5480000|title=Vocal Sampling - Akapelleando|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=2019-12-01}}</ref>\n* [[Bunker Beach]] waterpark has a rotating music set, called Splash Radio which includes a version of this song.\n* [[Gregory Isaacs]] covered the song under the \"Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)\" title.\n*[[The Hit Crew]] covered this song.\n* The cast of the hit Broadway musical ''[[Beetlejuice (musical)|Beetlejuice]]'' covered it in their finale.\n\n==Parodies and alternate lyrics==\n* \"Banana Boat (Day-O)\" a parody by [[Stan Freberg]], released in 1957 by [[Capitol Records]], features ongoing disagreement between an enthusiastic Jamaican lead singer and a [[bongo drums|bongo]]-playing [[beatnik]] (Peter Leeds) who \"don't dig loud noises\" and has the catchphrase \"You're too loud, man\". When he hears the lyric about the \"deadly black [[tarantula|taranch-la]]\" (actually the highly venomous [[Brazilian wandering spider]], commonly dubbed \"banana spider\"), the beatnik protests, \"No, man! Don't sing about ''spiders'', I mean, oooo! like I don't dig ''spiders''\". Freberg's version was popular and received much radio airplay; Harry Belafonte reportedly disliked the parody.<ref name=pc18>{{cite web|url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19768/m1/|title=Show 18 \u2013 Blowin' in the Wind: Pop discovers folk music. [Part 1&#93; : UNT Digital Library|website=Digital.library.unt.edu|date=1969-05-25|accessdate=2010-09-24}}</ref> Stan Freberg's version was the basis for the jingle for the [[Television advertisement|TV advert]] for the UK [[chocolate bar]] [[Trio (chocolate bar)|Trio]] from the mid-1980s to the early to mid-1990s, the lyrics being, \"Trio, Trio, I want a Trio and I want one now. Not one, not two, but three things in it; chocolatey biscuit and a toffee taste too.\"\n* Dutch comedian [[Andr\u00e9 van Duin]] released his version in 1972 called ''Het bananenlied'': the banana song. This song asks repetitively why bananas are bent. It reaches the conclusion that if the bananas weren't bent they wouldn't fit into their peels.\n* German band [[Trio (band)|Trio]] performed a parody where \"Bommerlunder\" (a German schnapps) substituted the words \"daylight come\" in the 1980s. In one rare occurrence, Trio and Harry Belafonte appeared in the same TV show, \"Bio's Bahnhof\", in 1982,  with the latter watching Trio's act in disbelief.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sF8n9MDkXRw#t=525 |title=Trio bei Bio |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2011-11-16 |accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref>\n* The [[Serbia]]n comedy rock band [[The Kuguars]], consisting of famous Serbian actors, covered the song in 1998, with lyrics in [[Serbian language]] dedicated to the, at the time, [[FR Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] national [[soccer]] team player [[Dejan Savi\u0107evi\u0107|Dejan \"Dejo\" Savi\u0107evi\u0107]]. The song became a nationwide hit, and a promotional video for the song had been recorded.\n* In their 1994 album, the comedy music group [[Grup Vitamin]] included a Turkish cover of the song parodying the [[Machismo|macho culture]] in the country.\n*The Swedish humor show [[:sv:Rally (radioprogram)|Rally]], which aired between 1995 and 2002 in [[Sveriges Radio P3]] made a version called \"Hey Mr. Taliban\", which speaks about Osama Bin Laden with the lyrics \"Hey Mister Tallyman, tally me banana/Daylight come and me wan' go home\" replaced by \"Hey Mister Taliban, In Afghanistan/US Come and you wanna go home\" or \"Hey Mister Taliban! Turn over Bin Laden\" and \"Day-O! Daaaaay-O! Daylight come and me wan' go home\" is replaced by \"Day-O! Daaaay-O! Missile come and you wanna go home\".\n* Since 1988 British radio [[DJ]] and presenter [[Simon Mayo]] has used several variations of the song as jingles. This originated during Mayo's time as presenter of the [[Radio 1 Breakfast Show]] where the jingle was sung by fellow presenter [[Steve Wright (DJ)|Steve Wright]] and has continued on many of his shows since, including Mayo's [[Simon Mayo Drivetime|Drivetime]] show on [[BBC Radio 2]] and since 2019 an orchestral version on Mayo's mid-morning show on [[Scala Radio]].\n* In 1988\u201389, Belafonte's children, David and Gina, parodied the song in a commercial about the [[Oldsmobile Toronado]] Trofeo. (David was singing \"Trofeo\" in the same style as \"Day-O\" in the song). \n* A parody of this song was used in an [[E-Trade]] commercial that first aired on [[Super Bowl LII]]\n*Food manufacturer [[Kellogg's]] parodied the song in their 2001 television advertisement for their breakfast cereal [[Fruit 'n Fibre]].\n* For an ad campaign that started in 1991, now-defunct Seattle-based department store chain [[The Bon March\u00e9|Bon Marche]] used a version of the song with alternate lyrics in their commercials.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Banel |first1=Feliks |title=The unlikely lasting legacy, melody from the Bon March\u00e9 |url=http://mynorthwest.com/392044/lasting-melody-from-bon-marche/? |website=Mynorthwest.com |accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n*In November 2019, the Stephen Colbert show modified the lyrics to make fun of [[Mike Pompeo]], saying \"Pompe-O, Pompe-O. Hearing come and I wanna go home.\" and continuing with \"Clearly we all knew of quid pro quo\", \"We all knew of the Ukraine deal\", \"Soon [[Adam Schiff|Mr. Adam man]] will issue him subpoena\", \"Run Mr. Flabby Man, Run back to Kansas\", with each line followed by \"Hearing come and I wanna go home.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-colbert-taunts-mike-pompeo-calypso-song-sung-by-trump-bolton-pence-video/|title=Stephen Colbert Taunts Mike Pompeo With a Goodbye Calypso Tune|website=Thewrap.com|date=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Samples and interpolations==\n* Country music artist [[Neal McCoy]] references the song in his song \"Hillbilly Rap\" off his 1996 [[Neal McCoy (album)|self-titled album]].\n* Jamaican singer [[Frankie Paul]] used the song's chorus for a dancehall song.\n* [[Jason Derulo]] sampled the song in \"[[Don't Wanna Go Home]]\".\n* American rapper [[Lil Wayne]] samples the line \"6 foot, 7 foot, 8 foot bunch\" for the hook of the song \"[[6 Foot 7 Foot]]\", together with the line \"Stack Banana\" which is repeated throughout the song.\n* Chilean program ''[[31 minutos]]'' used the song \"Arwrarwrirwrarwro\" make a Bombi version of \"Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.31minutos.cl/codex/arwrarwrirwrarwro/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-08-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725070552/http://www.31minutos.cl/codex/arwrarwrirwrarwro/ |archive-date=2017-07-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Singer-songwriter [[Gotye]] sampled the song in his single [[Hearts a Mess]].\n\n==In media and politics==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=October 2017}}\n* Belafonte sang the song on a 1979 episode of ''[[The Muppet Show]]'', the first time he performed it on television since 1955.\n* [[Fleksnes Fataliteter]] The Norwegian comedy character Marve Fleksnes uses the phrase \"Day-O\" whenever he sees a situation which he can benefit from, or when agitated or insecure.\n* In the [[Bosom Buddies]] episode \"Only The Lonely\", Ruth invites Kip and Henry to her apartment for a get-together, but keeps the party going until all hours and won't let the pair leave. When she starts singing the Banana Boat Song, Kip and Henry only join in on the chorus: \"We want to go home\".\n* The original 1956 Belafonte recording is heard in the 1988 film ''[[Beetlejuice]]'' in a dinner scene in which the guests are supernaturally compelled to dance along to the song by the film's protagonists. \n** It was also sung by Beetlejuice and Lydia in the first episode of the [[Beetlejuice (TV series)|animated series]].\n** The scene from the film is recreated as the first act finale in the [[musical theatre|Broadway]] [[Beetlejuice (musical)|musical adaptation]].\n* Belafonte's version was used in a 1990s [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] ident featuring the ''[[Bananas in Pyjamas]]''.\n* On the [[NFL Primetime]] program, [[Chris Berman]] uses the phrase \"Daylight come and you gotta Delhomme\", as a nickname for former [[Carolina Panthers]] quarterback [[Jake Delhomme]].\n* In [[Ava DuVernay]]'s film ''[[Selma (film)|Selma]]'', Rev. [[Hosea Williams]] (played by [[Wendell Pierce]]) starts a chorus of the song at a meeting where it is announced that [[Harry Belafonte]] will join the third and final of the [[Selma to Montgomery marches]]. Belafonte appears among the marchers in newsreel footage shown during the end credits of the film.\n* In [[Thomas & Friends]] ''[[Sodor's Legend of the Lost Treasure]]'', Skiff the Railboat ([[Jamie Campbell Bower]]) sings a part of the chorus after he sees the sun comes up, whilst calling Sailor John ([[John Hurt]]) out that it is time to go home.\n* In [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 23)]], [[Terra Jole]] and [[Sasha Farber]] danced to this song in the special \"Halloween Dance Night.\"\n* In the ''[[Legends of Tomorrow]]'' episode \"Moonshot\", [[Firestorm (comics)#Martin Stein|Martin Stein]] ([[Victor Garber]]) and [[Heat Wave (comics)|Mick Rory]] ([[Dominic Purcell]]) sing a duet version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/recap/legends-of-tomorrow-season-2-episode-14/|title='Legends of Tomorrow' Recap: Defying Gravity, Legends-Style|date=15 March 2017|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n* In the TV series ''[[Family Ties]]'' episode \"Invasion of the Psychologist Snatchers\", Lauren ([[Courteney Cox]]) tells Alex ([[Michael J. Fox]]) she loves him because he once started singing the song when they were attending a very boring conference.\n* The song was used in the 1989 unsold animated pilot ''Hound Town''.{{citation needed|reason=presumably documented only by the contributor's recollection, in absence of RS|date=November 2018}}\n* In the \"Tickle Me Land\" scene of the \"Bananas\" episode of the ''[[Sesame Street]]'' segment, ''[[Elmo's World]]'', Elmo in sung a few lines of the song while dressed as a banana.\n* In the Late Show by Stephen Colbert, Day-O was modified to Pompe-O.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* The song was also the wake-up call for the astronauts on two [[Space Shuttle]] missions in the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/world-news/writer-of-harry-belafontes-calypso-hit-dayo-dies-aged-95-38742378.html|title=Writer of Harry Belafonte\u2019s calypso hit Day-O dies aged 95|website=Belfasttelegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Justin Trudeau blackface incident===\n{{See also|Justin Trudeau blackface controversy}}\nOn September 18, 2019, [[Justin Trudeau]], the Prime Minister of [[Canada]], admitted to singing \"Day-O\" while wearing [[blackface]] makeup and an [[afro]] wig at a talent show when he was in high school at [[Coll\u00e8ge Jean-de-Br\u00e9beuf]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5680868/justin-trudeau-brownface-photo-apology/|title=Justin Trudeau Admits to Also Wearing Blackface 'Makeup' in High School Following TIME Report|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|language=en|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fremeaux.com/index.php?option=com_virtuemart&page=shop.livrets&content_id=5362&product_id=1176&category_id=128 English version of the text can be found at the bottom of the page. These lyrics are different from Belafonte's original version]\n* [http://soquoted.blogspot.com/2005/09/who-wrote-banana-boat-song.html Who wrote the Banana Boat Song?], So Quoted blog, September 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110918041119/http://www.originals.be/en/originals.php?id=1264 \"Banana Loader's Song], The Originals website \n* [http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/news/environment/the-banana-boat-song-daylight-come-and-me-wan-go-home-612177/ Mark Roth, \"The Banana Boat Song: 'Daylight come and me wan' go home ...'\"], ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]],'' 27 November 2005\n\n{{Beetlejuice}}\n{{Harry Belafonte}}\n{{Sarah Vaughan}}\n{{Steve Lawrence}}\n\n[[Category:Jamaican songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Germany]]\n[[Category:1956 singles]]\n[[Category:1957 singles]]\n[[Category:Harry Belafonte songs]]\n[[Category:The Fontane Sisters songs]]\n[[Category:Shirley Bassey songs]]\n[[Category:Calypso songs]]\n[[Category:Bananas in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Songs about plants]]\n[[Category:Songs about labor]]\n[[Category:Songs about food]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Year of song unknown]]\n[[Category:Songwriter unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Day-O|the television film|Day-O (film)}}\n{{For|the song that samples the lyric \"6 foot, 7 foot, 8 foot bunch\"|6 Foot 7 Foot}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name        = Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)\n| cover       = \n| alt         =\n| type        = single\n| artist      = [[Harry Belafonte]]\n| album       = [[Calypso (album)|Calypso]]\n| B-side      = \"Star-O\"\n| released    = 1956\n| format      = [[Vinyl record]] (7-inch, 10-inch)\n| recorded    = 1955\n| studio      = Grand Ballroom, [[Webster Hall]], [[New York City]]\n| venue       = \n| genre       = [[Mento]]\n| length      = 3:02\n| label       = [[RCA Victor]]\n| writer      = \n| producer    =\n| prev_title  = [[Mary's Boy Child]]\n| prev_year   = 1954\n| next_title  = Hold 'Em Joe\n| next_year   = 1957\n}}\n[[File:Harry Belafonte Almanac 1954 b.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Harry Belafonte, Almanac, 1954 Feb. 18.]]\n\n'''\"Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)\"''' is a traditional [[Music of Jamaica|Jamaican folk song]]. The song has [[mento]] influences, but it is commonly classified as an example of the better known [[calypso music]].\n\nIt is a [[work song]], from the point of view of dock workers working the night shift loading [[banana]]s onto ships. The lyrics describe how daylight has come, their shift is over, and they want their work to be counted up so that they can go home.\n\nThe best-known version was released by American singer [[Harry Belafonte]] in 1956 and later became one of his signature songs. That same year [[The Tarriers]] released an alternative version that incorporated the chorus of another Jamaican [[folk song]], \"Hill and Gully Rider\". The Tarriers version was recorded by [[Shirley Bassey]] in 1957<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Shirley-Bassey-The-Banana-Boat-Song/master/1461636</ref> for her 1959 album ''[[The Bewitching Miss Bassey]]''.<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Shirley-Bassey-The-Bewitching-Miss-Bassey/master/648488</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nThe song originated as a Jamaican folk song. It was thought to be sung by Jamaican banana workers, with a repeated melody and refrain ([[Call and response (music)|call and response]]); to each set lyric, the workers made a response. There were numerous versions of lyrics, some likely improvised on the spot by the singers. The song was probably created around the second half of the nineteenth century or the first half of the twentieth century, where there was [[History of Jamaica#Decline of the sugar industry|a rise of the banana trade in Jamaica]].\n\nThe song was first recorded by [[Trinidad]]ian singer [[Edric Connor]] and his band \"Edric Connor and the Caribbeans\" on the 1952 album ''Songs From Jamaica''; the song was called \"Day Dah Light\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mentomusic.com/edricConner.htm |title=Edric Connor, Louise Bennett and Jamaican Folk Music |publisher=Mento Music |date= |accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref> Belafonte based his version on Connor's 1952 and [[Louise Bennett]]'s 1954 recordings.<ref>The Louise Bennett version of ''Day O (The Banana Boat Song)'' is available and documented in both French and English on the ''Jamaica &ndash; Mento 1951&ndash;1958'' album (2009)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fremeaux.com/index.php?option=com_virtuemart&page=shop.livrets&content_id=5362&product_id=1176&category_id=128 |title=Fr\u00e9meaux & Associ\u00e9s \u00e9diteur, La Librairie Sonore |website=Fremeaux.com |date=1932-06-19 |accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1955, American singer-songwriters [[Lord Burgess]] and [[William Attaway]] wrote a version of the lyrics for ''[[the Colgate Comedy Hour]]'', in which the song was performed by [[Harry Belafonte]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dGSnsW6rA6EC&pg=PA186|title=Trinidad Carnival: The Cultural Politics of a Transnational Festival|first1=Garth L.|last1=Green|first2=Philip W.|last2=Scher|date=28 March 2007|page=186|publisher=[[Indiana University Press]]|accessdate=1 September 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref> Belafonte recorded the song for [[RCA Victor]]  and this is the version that is best known to listeners today, as it reached number five on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' charts in 1957 and later became Belafonte's [[signature song]]. Side two of Belafonte's 1956 ''Calypso'' album opens with \"Star O\", a song referring to the day shift ending when the first star is seen in the sky. During recording, when asked for its title, Harry spells, \"Day Done Light\".\n\nAlso in 1956, folk singer [[Bob Gibson (musician)|Bob Gibson]], who had traveled to Jamaica and heard the song, taught his version to the folk band [[The Tarriers]]. They recorded a version of that song that incorporated the chorus of \"Hill and Gully Rider\", another Jamaican folk song. This release became their biggest hit, reaching number four on the pop charts, where it outperformed Belafonte's version. The Tarriers' version was recorded by [[Shirley Bassey]] in 1957 and it became a hit in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/The%20Banana%20Boat%20Song |title=ChartArchive - Shirley Bassey - The Banana Boat Song |website=Archive.is |date= |accessdate=2016-08-22 |df= }}</ref> The Tarriers, or some subset of the three members of the group ([[Erik Darling]], [[Bob Carey (musician)|Bob Carey]] and [[Alan Arkin]], later better known as an actor) are sometimes credited as the writers of the song; their version combined elements of another song and was thus newly created.\n\n== Covers ==\n* [[Sarah Vaughan]] recorded the song for [[Mercury Records]] in 1956.\n* [[The Fontane Sisters]] mimicked The Tarriers version in a recording of the song for [[Dot Records]] in 1956.  It charted to number 13 in the US in 1957.\n* [[Barry Frank]] released a version for Bell in 1957.<ref name=bell>{{cite web | title = Barry Frank recorded or participated in at least the following 54 song(s) | url = http://www.bellrecords.nl/?wp=performers| publisher = Bell Records | accessdate = 8 October 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Jimmie Rodgers (pop singer)|Jimmie Rodgers]] recorded the song for [[Dot Records]] which was released in September, 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Jimmie-Rodgers-The-Banana-Boat-Song/release/4702109 |title=Jimmie Rodgers (2) - The Banana Boat Song (Vinyl) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref>\n* [[The Techniques]] covered the song in 1967.\n* [[The Kinks]] did a semi-serious version on the 1972 album ''[[Everybody's in Show-Biz]]''\n* Children's singer [[Raffi (musician)|Raffi]] recorded this song for his 1980 album, ''[[Baby Beluga]]'', releasing it as a single. \n* Italian singer [[Mina (Italian singer)|Mina]] covered the song under the title \"Banana Boat\" on the 1984 album [[Catene (album)|Catene]].\n* [[Chuck Brown|Chuck Brown & the Soul Searchers]] performed a [[go-go]] rendition for the album ''[[Go Go Swing Live]]'' (1986).\n* [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]] released a Funk version of the song on his 1989 album ''[[The Cinderella Theory]]''.\n* [[Hasil Adkins]] recorded a [[rockabilly]] version of this song that was included on the 1990 [[Norton Records]] album, ''[[Peanut Butter Rock and Roll]]''.\n* Jamaican singer [[Shaggy (musician)|Shaggy]] recorded a dancehall version for his 1995 album ''[[Boombastic (album)|Boombastic]]''.\n* The Kidsongs Kids sing this song on \"I'd Like to Teach the World to Sing\". There is also an instrumental [[Outro (music)|outro]] as heard on CDs and cassettes.\n* German dance band [[Scooter (band)|Scooter]] made a cover version of the song in 2003. Originally, it was intended to release as a Ratty track but the plan cancelled and the song released under the name \"Beetle Juice pres. Rick Maniac & Dr. Loop\".\n* The Polish sea-shanty band [[Banana Boat]] sings this song on their 2004 album \"A morze tak, a mo\u017ce nie\".\n* British [[New wave music|new wave]] band [[The Police (band)|The Police]] were known to include snippets of the song during early live performances of their own track '[[Reggatta de Blanc (instrumental)|Reggatta de Blanc]]'.\n* Australian children's entertainers [[The Wiggles]] cover it in their 2008 album ''[[You Make Me Feel Like Dancing (album)|You Make Me Feel Like Dancing]]''.\n* [[Vocal Sampling]] have performed an [[a cappella]] version, which is included in their 2008 album ''Akapelleando''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Vocal-Sampling-Akapelleando/release/5480000|title=Vocal Sampling - Akapelleando|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=2019-12-01}}</ref>\n* [[Bunker Beach]] waterpark has a rotating music set, called Splash Radio which includes a version of this song.\n* [[Gregory Isaacs]] covered the song under the \"Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)\" title.\n*[[The Hit Crew]] covered this song.\n* The cast of the hit Broadway musical ''[[Beetlejuice (musical)|Beetlejuice]]'' covered it in their finale.\n\n==Parodies and alternate lyrics==\n* \"Banana Boat (Day-O)\" a parody by [[Stan Freberg]], released in 1957 by [[Capitol Records]], features ongoing disagreement between an enthusiastic Jamaican lead singer and a [[bongo drums|bongo]]-playing [[beatnik]] (Peter Leeds) who \"don't dig loud noises\" and has the catchphrase \"You're too loud, man\". When he hears the lyric about the \"deadly black [[tarantula|taranch-la]]\" (actually the highly venomous [[Brazilian wandering spider]], commonly dubbed \"banana spider\"), the beatnik protests, \"No, man! Don't sing about ''spiders'', I mean, oooo! like I don't dig ''spiders''\". Freberg's version was popular and received much radio airplay; Harry Belafonte reportedly disliked the parody.<ref name=pc18>{{cite web|url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc19768/m1/|title=Show 18 \u2013 Blowin' in the Wind: Pop discovers folk music. [Part 1&#93; : UNT Digital Library|website=Digital.library.unt.edu|date=1969-05-25|accessdate=2010-09-24}}</ref> Stan Freberg's version was the basis for the jingle for the [[Television advertisement|TV advert]] for the UK [[chocolate bar]] [[Trio (chocolate bar)|Trio]] from the mid-1980s to the early to mid-1990s, the lyrics being, \"Trio, Trio, I want a Trio and I want one now. Not one, not two, but three things in it; chocolatey biscuit and a toffee taste too.\"\n* Dutch comedian [[Andr\u00e9 van Duin]] released his version in 1972 called ''Het bananenlied'': the banana song. This song asks repetitively why bananas are bent. It reaches the conclusion that if the bananas weren't bent they wouldn't fit into their peels.\n* German band [[Trio (band)|Trio]] performed a parody where \"Bommerlunder\" (a German schnapps) substituted the words \"daylight come\" in the 1980s. In one rare occurrence, Trio and Harry Belafonte appeared in the same TV show, \"Bio's Bahnhof\", in 1982,  with the latter watching Trio's act in disbelief.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sF8n9MDkXRw#t=525 |title=Trio bei Bio |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2011-11-16 |accessdate=2016-08-22}}</ref>\n* The [[Serbia]]n comedy rock band [[The Kuguars]], consisting of famous Serbian actors, covered the song in 1998, with lyrics in [[Serbian language]] dedicated to the, at the time, [[FR Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] national [[soccer]] team player [[Dejan Savi\u0107evi\u0107|Dejan \"Dejo\" Savi\u0107evi\u0107]]. The song became a nationwide hit, and a promotional video for the song had been recorded.\n* In their 1994 album, the comedy music group [[Grup Vitamin]] included a Turkish cover of the song parodying the [[Machismo|macho culture]] in the country.\n*The Swedish humor show [[:sv:Rally (radioprogram)|Rally]], which aired between 1995 and 2002 in [[Sveriges Radio P3]] made a version called \"Hey Mr. Taliban\", which speaks about Osama Bin Laden with the lyrics \"Hey Mister Tallyman, tally me banana/Daylight come and me wan' go home\" replaced by \"Hey Mister Taliban, In Afghanistan/US Come and you wanna go home\" or \"Hey Mister Taliban! Turn over Bin Laden\" and \"Day-O! Daaaaay-O! Daylight come and me wan' go home\" is replaced by \"Day-O! Daaaay-O! Missile come and you wanna go home\".\n* Since 1988 British radio [[DJ]] and presenter [[Simon Mayo]] has used several variations of the song as jingles. This originated during Mayo's time as presenter of the [[Radio 1 Breakfast Show]] where the jingle was sung by fellow presenter [[Steve Wright (DJ)|Steve Wright]] and has continued on many of his shows since, including Mayo's [[Simon Mayo Drivetime|Drivetime]] show on [[BBC Radio 2]] and since 2019 an orchestral version on Mayo's mid-morning show on [[Scala Radio]].\n* In 1988\u201389, Belafonte's children, David and Gina, parodied the song in a commercial about the [[Oldsmobile Toronado]] Trofeo. (David was singing \"Trofeo\" in the same style as \"Day-O\" in the song). \n* A parody of this song was used in an [[E-Trade]] commercial that first aired on [[Super Bowl LII]]\n*Food manufacturer [[Kellogg's]] parodied the song in their 2001 television advertisement for their breakfast cereal [[Fruit 'n Fibre]].\n* For an ad campaign that started in 1991, now-defunct Seattle-based department store chain [[The Bon March\u00e9|Bon Marche]] used a version of the song with alternate lyrics in their commercials.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Banel |first1=Feliks |title=The unlikely lasting legacy, melody from the Bon March\u00e9 |url=http://mynorthwest.com/392044/lasting-melody-from-bon-marche/? |website=Mynorthwest.com |accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n*In November 2019, the Stephen Colbert show modified the lyrics to make fun of [[Mike Pompeo]], saying \"Pompe-O, Pompe-O. Hearing come and I wanna go home.\" and continuing with \"Clearly we all knew of quid pro quo\", \"We all knew of the Ukraine deal\", \"Soon [[Adam Schiff|Mr. Adam man]] will issue him subpoena\", \"Run Mr. Flabby Man, Run back to Kansas\", with each line followed by \"Hearing come and I wanna go home.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/stephen-colbert-taunts-mike-pompeo-calypso-song-sung-by-trump-bolton-pence-video/|title=Stephen Colbert Taunts Mike Pompeo With a Goodbye Calypso Tune|website=Thewrap.com|date=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Samples and interpolations==\n* Country music artist [[Neal McCoy]] references the song in his song \"Hillbilly Rap\" off his 1996 [[Neal McCoy (album)|self-titled album]].\n* Jamaican singer [[Frankie Paul]] used the song's chorus for a dancehall song.\n* [[Jason Derulo]] sampled the song in \"[[Don't Wanna Go Home]]\".\n* American rapper [[Lil Wayne]] samples the line \"6 foot, 7 foot, 8 foot bunch\" for the hook of the song \"[[6 Foot 7 Foot]]\", together with the line \"Stack Banana\" which is repeated throughout the song.\n* Chilean program ''[[31 minutos]]'' used the song \"Arwrarwrirwrarwro\" make a Bombi version of \"Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.31minutos.cl/codex/arwrarwrirwrarwro/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-08-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725070552/http://www.31minutos.cl/codex/arwrarwrirwrarwro/ |archive-date=2017-07-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==In media and politics==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=October 2017}}\n* Belafonte sang the song on a 1979 episode of ''[[The Muppet Show]]'', the first time he performed it on television since 1955.\n* [[Fleksnes Fataliteter]] The Norwegian comedy character Marve Fleksnes uses the phrase \"Day-O\" whenever he sees a situation which he can benefit from, or when agitated or insecure.\n* In the [[Bosom Buddies]] episode \"Only The Lonely\", Ruth invites Kip and Henry to her apartment for a get-together, but keeps the party going until all hours and won't let the pair leave. When she starts singing the Banana Boat Song, Kip and Henry only join in on the chorus: \"We want to go home\".\n* The original 1956 Belafonte recording is heard in the 1988 film ''[[Beetlejuice]]'' in a dinner scene in which the guests are supernaturally compelled to dance along to the song by the film's protagonists. \n** It was also sung by Beetlejuice and Lydia in the first episode of the [[Beetlejuice (TV series)|animated series]].\n** The scene from the film is recreated as the first act finale in the [[musical theatre|Broadway]] [[Beetlejuice (musical)|musical adaptation]].\n* Belafonte's version was used in a 1990s [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] ident featuring the ''[[Bananas in Pyjamas]]''.\n* On the [[NFL Primetime]] program, [[Chris Berman]] uses the phrase \"Daylight come and you gotta Delhomme\", as a nickname for former [[Carolina Panthers]] quarterback [[Jake Delhomme]].\n* In [[Ava DuVernay]]'s film ''[[Selma (film)|Selma]]'', Rev. [[Hosea Williams]] (played by [[Wendell Pierce]]) starts a chorus of the song at a meeting where it is announced that [[Harry Belafonte]] will join the third and final of the [[Selma to Montgomery marches]]. Belafonte appears among the marchers in newsreel footage shown during the end credits of the film.\n* In [[Thomas & Friends]] ''[[Sodor's Legend of the Lost Treasure]]'', Skiff the Railboat ([[Jamie Campbell Bower]]) sings a part of the chorus after he sees the sun comes up, whilst calling Sailor John ([[John Hurt]]) out that it is time to go home.\n* In [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 23)]], [[Terra Jole]] and [[Sasha Farber]] danced to this song in the special \"Halloween Dance Night.\"\n* In the ''[[Legends of Tomorrow]]'' episode \"Moonshot\", [[Firestorm (comics)#Martin Stein|Martin Stein]] ([[Victor Garber]]) and [[Heat Wave (comics)|Mick Rory]] ([[Dominic Purcell]]) sing a duet version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/recap/legends-of-tomorrow-season-2-episode-14/|title='Legends of Tomorrow' Recap: Defying Gravity, Legends-Style|date=15 March 2017|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n* In the TV series ''[[Family Ties]]'' episode \"Invasion of the Psychologist Snatchers\", Lauren ([[Courteney Cox]]) tells Alex ([[Michael J. Fox]]) she loves him because he once started singing the song when they were attending a very boring conference.\n* The song was used in the 1989 unsold animated pilot ''Hound Town''.{{citation needed|reason=presumably documented only by the contributor's recollection, in absence of RS|date=November 2018}}\n* In the \"Tickle Me Land\" scene of the \"Bananas\" episode of the ''[[Sesame Street]]'' segment, ''[[Elmo's World]]'', Elmo in sung a few lines of the song while dressed as a banana.\n* In the Late Show by Stephen Colbert, Day-O was modified to Pompe-O.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* The song was also the wake-up call for the astronauts on two [[Space Shuttle]] missions in the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/world-news/writer-of-harry-belafontes-calypso-hit-dayo-dies-aged-95-38742378.html|title=Writer of Harry Belafonte\u2019s calypso hit Day-O dies aged 95|website=Belfasttelegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Justin Trudeau blackface incident===\n{{See also|Justin Trudeau blackface controversy}}\nOn September 18, 2019, [[Justin Trudeau]], the Prime Minister of [[Canada]], admitted to singing \"Day-O\" while wearing [[blackface]] makeup and an [[afro]] wig at a talent show when he was in high school at [[Coll\u00e8ge Jean-de-Br\u00e9beuf]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5680868/justin-trudeau-brownface-photo-apology/|title=Justin Trudeau Admits to Also Wearing Blackface 'Makeup' in High School Following TIME Report|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|language=en|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fremeaux.com/index.php?option=com_virtuemart&page=shop.livrets&content_id=5362&product_id=1176&category_id=128 English version of the text can be found at the bottom of the page. These lyrics are different from Belafonte's original version]\n* [http://soquoted.blogspot.com/2005/09/who-wrote-banana-boat-song.html Who wrote the Banana Boat Song?], So Quoted blog, September 2005\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110918041119/http://www.originals.be/en/originals.php?id=1264 \"Banana Loader's Song], The Originals website \n* [http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/news/environment/the-banana-boat-song-daylight-come-and-me-wan-go-home-612177/ Mark Roth, \"The Banana Boat Song: 'Daylight come and me wan' go home ...'\"], ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]],'' 27 November 2005\n\n{{Beetlejuice}}\n{{Harry Belafonte}}\n{{Sarah Vaughan}}\n{{Steve Lawrence}}\n\n[[Category:Jamaican songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Germany]]\n[[Category:1956 singles]]\n[[Category:1957 singles]]\n[[Category:Harry Belafonte songs]]\n[[Category:The Fontane Sisters songs]]\n[[Category:Shirley Bassey songs]]\n[[Category:Calypso songs]]\n[[Category:Bananas in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Songs about plants]]\n[[Category:Songs about labor]]\n[[Category:S